---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { getContactLinks, siteConfig } from "../site";

const contactLinks = getContactLinks();
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="About Juha Huotari and kotona.app: a public field notebook on data platforms, infrastructure, agent-assisted engineering, and operational systems."
  pageType="profile"
>
  <section class="page-intro">
    <p class="eyebrow">About</p>
    <h1 class="page-title">{siteConfig.profile.name}</h1>

    <p class="page-copy">
      I’m a solution analyst in Finland working on data platforms and
      integration-heavy systems. My background spans insurance data platforms
      and regulatory reporting in wealth management—usually where business
      rules, operational processes, and durable data have to agree.
    </p>

    <h2>This site</h2>

    <p class="page-copy">
      kotona.app is a public field notebook for systems, projects, and ideas
      that should remain understandable after the first successful run.
    </p>

    <p class="page-copy">
      The core subjects are data platforms, declarative infrastructure,
      contract-first software, and agent-assisted engineering. The site also
      contains bounded explorations in energy, hardware, organizational systems,
      and the built environment when the useful question is whether an idea can
      survive its operational constraints.
    </p>

    <p class="page-copy">
      The common thread is how authority, state, evidence, boundaries, and
      recovery fit together when a system has to keep working, evolving, and
      being understood.
    </p>

    <h2>How to read it</h2>

    <p class="page-copy">
      <strong>Projects</strong> describe things that exist: what they do, how they
      are shaped, their current state, and when that state was last verified.
    </p>

    <p class="page-copy">
      <strong>Notes</strong> preserve decisions, failures, operating rules, and reference
      models worth retrieving later. Their lifecycle describes how they should be
      interpreted: guiding notes are in current use, prospective notes describe a
      direction, explorations test an idea, and archival notes preserve useful context
      without claiming to be current guidance.
    </p>

    <p class="page-copy">
      Explorations are developed beyond casual speculation, but they are not
      automatically plans, forecasts, or recommendations. Sometimes the analysis
      is the product.
    </p>

    <p class="page-copy">
      The writing is usually compact, declarative, and evidence-led. It serves
      both as public explanation and as durable retrieval material for future
      work. Some notes use a more personal or creative register when the subject
      benefits from it.
    </p>

    <h2>Agents and authorship</h2>

    <p class="page-copy">
      Agents contribute substantially to the inspection, comparison,
      implementation, and drafting behind this site. I provide the source
      material and constraints, make the corrections, verify the claims, and
      decide what is published.
    </p>

    <p class="page-copy">
      Generated output is working material. The published claim is mine.
    </p>

    <p class="page-copy">
      For a longer account of the site’s authorship and editorial process, see
      <a href="/notes/the-workshop-is-learning-my-accent/">
        <cite>The workshop is learning my accent</cite>
      </a>.
    </p>

    <p class="page-copy">
      This is a personal site. The views published here are my own and do not
      represent my employer.
    </p>

    {
      contactLinks.length > 0 && (
        <ul class="link-row" aria-label="Contact and external profiles">
          {contactLinks.map((link) => (
            <li>
              <a
                class="link-chip"
                href={link.href}
                rel={link.href.startsWith("http") ? "me noreferrer" : undefined}
              >
                {link.label}
              </a>
            </li>
          ))}
        </ul>
      )
    }
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
